{
  "text": "Leaflet degeneration per se is suggested by concomitant observations of increased leaflet and/or chordal thickness [CITATION_1] , MV prolapse [CITATION_2] and ruptured chordae [CITATION_3] . However, controversies about the frequency of myxomatous leaflet degeneration, similar to that observed in Barlow's disease, exist in the literature. In a large anatomical study of patients with obstructive HCM, there was no histopathological myxomatous change in the spongiosa of excised MVs [CITATION_4] . Conversely, myxomatous degeneration was found in case reports of HCM patients with massive MR caused by chordal rupture [CITATION_5] , and was suggested with a markedly high frequency in a large surgical cohort of patients with obstructive HCM [CITATION_6] . Histological evidence of massive myxomatous degeneration involving the leaflet and its chordae was consistently retrieved in the current study and might constitute a substrate for rupture in that setting.",
  "correct_citation": {
